lace \"extra\" repeat units in the gap region between the SSR and the first adjacent base to the left of the SSR, while Genious mapper tends to place \"extra\" repeat units to the right of the SSR, in the gap between the SSR and the first adjacent base<\/li><li style = \"counter-reset:ol0;list-style-type:disc;\">For each read the Geneious \"Extract\" function was used to select bases within the ROI to create a new FASTQ file of CCS with bases spanning the ROI.<\/li><\/ul><\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/83pjrq6.png\" \/><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Portion of CCS spanning the region of interest<\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"AE36CE3814BE477EBF5A12F8B8FFFBC8","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/83pjrq6.png\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#E57785","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":849085,"guid":"41DD97099C404C61ACF3DDF4461A7C9A","previous_id":849084,"previous_guid":"263EA10C00814CE2A59A26D8C253BB37","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"612E7DEC8AF047C2B1AE7D0E1D7CF768","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Extract region of interest from each read into FASTQ file."}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"9C7267057C0F4C248126E6E4784BAF9A","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Create the following FASTQ reads for downstream analysis in MATLAB (link to CodeOcean capsule)<\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"0983EA60D7B611E8945595E356F0D10B","order_id":2,"type_id":23,"title":"file","source":{"source":"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/878jrq6.fastq","placeholder":"\/img\/extensions\/file.png","original_name":"SRR8080935_79bp_AAGC_SSR_ROI_reads.fastq"}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"11E30330D7B611E8945595E356F0D10B","order_id":3,"type_id":23,"title":"file","source":{"source":"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/879jrq6.fastq","placeholder":"\/img\/extensions\/file.png","original_name":"SRR8080935_107bp_ACTG_SSR_ROI_reads.fastq"}},{"id":1054727,"guid":"1B7285B0D7B611E8945595E356F0D10B","order_id":4,"type_id":23,"title":"file","source":{"source":"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/88ajrq6.fastq","placeholder":"\/img\/extensions\/file.png","original_name":"SRR8080935_147bp_ACTG_SSR_ROI_reads.fastq"}},{"id":1054728,"guid":"24236800D7B611E8945595E356F0D10B","order_id":5,"type_id":23,"title":"file","source":{"source":"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/88bjrq6.fastq","placeholder":"\/img\/extensions\/file.png","original_name":"SRR8080935_154bp_AATC_SSR_ROI_reads.fastq"}},{"id":1054729,"guid":"2DCF2510D7B611E8945595E356F0D10B","order_id":6,"type_id":23,"title":"file","source":{"source":"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/88cjrq6.fastq","placeholder":"\/img\/extensions\/file.png","original_name":"SRR8080935_250bp_AACC_SSR_ROI_reads.fastq"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#EA94FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":849086,"guid":"CB171558E8E54BE7AF524E9B9DB2C8AB","previous_id":849085,"previous_guid":"41DD97099C404C61ACF3DDF4461A7C9A","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"3128D129383F4D678A14B13D882D619E","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Computed processes in Matlab for pruning reads to reveal reads representing extant molecules   "}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"FE4D0CE3FB514DEA9165EDF604CA8ED3","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Matlab scripts for processing ROI CCS (above step)  are available for download and processing at <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><a href=\"https:\/\/codeocean.com\/capsule\/2a31f701-1a37-4f5a-9a1e-d77230a0aad9\/code\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">Matlab  Compute Capsule<\/span><\/a><\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/ba5ga.png\" \/><\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"70F0026A7B33491E86E46E286B0AB401","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/ba5ga.png\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":null,"materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>The virulence and pathogenicity of bacterial pathogens are related to their adaptability to changing environments.  One\u00a0process enabling adaptation is based on minor changes in genome sequence, as small as a few base pairs, within segments of genome called simple sequence repeats (SSRs) that consist of multiple copies of a short sequence (from one to several nucleotides), repeated in series.\u00a0 SSRs\u00a0are found in eukaryotes\u00a0as well as prokaryotes, and variation in them occurs at frequencies up to a million-fold higher than the average bacterial mutation rate through a process of slipped stranded mispairing (SSM) by DNA polymerase during replication. The characterization of SSR length by standard sequencing methods is complicated by the appearance of length variation introduced during the sequencing process that does not accurately quantify lower-abundance repeat number variants in a population.  Here we report a computational approach to correct for process-induced artifacts, validated for tetranucleotide repeats by use of synthetic constructs of fixed, known length. We apply this method to a laboratory culture of<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Histophilus somni<\/span><span>, prepared from a single colony, and demonstrate that the culture consists of populations of distinct sequence phase and read length variants at individual tetranucleotide SSR loci.<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Input requirements: Closed Genome -   It is recommended that only organisms with closed genomes be the subject of the analyses described here. Mapping repetitive reads to to contigs of non-closed genomes may map to multiple locations, complicating tha analysis. Mapping CCS (circular consensus sequence) wiith repetitve sequence to closed genomes are guaranted  to map to a single locus if sufficent unique flanking sequence is used to confim the unique mapping.  Consequently, long CCS with high base quality are the most desirable input into this workflow.<\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/ba5fa.png\" \/><\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1574266876}